ame>Amy</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Burgess</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF031637%2F1"><gtr:id>A20BF435-5E02-4EC6-B6D9-6BB96685C075</gtr:id><gtr:title>Writing and Identity in Adult Literacy Education</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F031637/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This research focuses on writing and identity in adult literacy education.&amp;nbsp; It explores the kinds of identities as writers and as learners that literacy students develop and the connection between these identities and their development as writers.&amp;nbsp; It contributes to writing research by extending the theory of the construction of writer identity; to literacy theory by developing the concept of literacy practices; and to literacy studies methodology by elaborating the concept of literacy practices.&amp;nbsp; It also makes recommendations for pedagogy.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The aim of the Fellowship is to disseminate findings through publication in education and applied linguistics journals and presentation at academic conferences, as well as to prepare a proposal for further research.&amp;nbsp; The proposed research will investigate adult learners? uses of available texts and text types in their writing and the consequences of their uses of such texts for their writing development.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Writing is crucial to the knowledge economy and to participation in the democratic process.&amp;nbsp; Therefore research into how adults develop as writers fits well with policy aims of raising skill levels to enable the UK to compete successfully in the global economy, and of engaging more adults in the democratic process.
&lt;br />
